The College of Menominee Nation (CMN) is a tribal college in northeast Wisconsin, serving the tribes of Wisconsin as well as the non-Indian people in the surrounding communiites.  Through a number of National Science Foundation's (NSF) grants, CMN expanded and strenghtened its STEM and STEM-related course offerings, degrees, and academic support services.  As it built its STEM areas, CMN discerned that students who completed research-focused internship/externships during their academic career were far more likely to persist and complete their degrees than students who did not avail themselves of these opportunities.  To increase the possiblity that STEM students would complete research-focused intern/externships, CMN,  with NSF support, expanded its capacity to offer students a variety of research experiences.  During the 3-year project, CMN engaged in activities that would increase student awareness of research-focused intern/externships and prepare students to apply for intern/externships as well as created STEM internships,  and institutionalized its commitment to the Intern/Externship model.

With support from NSF, CMN:

located the intern/externship office within the Division of Student Services;

created a database of research-focused intern/externships;

supported student record system enhancement to include a intern/externship module;

recruited students through campus-wide emails and workshops;

provided workshops to students on cover letter, resume, and essay writing;

provided internships to STEM students;

provide STEM career-related field trips;

provided student travel to AISES conferences.





